04055nam a22005415i 9781447331384DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814473313847 a10.56687/97814473313842doi  a(DE-B1597)647373  a(OCoLC)1031344943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0130002bisacsh04a344.044qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aCahill, Suzanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDementia and Human Rights /cSuzanne Cahill. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (252 p.) :b3 Black and White  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of tables and figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tForeword -- tA conceptual framework -- tAn introduction to human rights and dementia -- tDementia as a disability -- tSetting the context: The UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities -- tUsing a human rights lens to interrogate policy and practice -- tThe right to a good quality of life at home and in the community -- tThe right to a good quality of life in care homes or in nursing homes -- tEmerging public policy on dementia: the implications of a human rights-based approach for policy and practice -- tLegal capacity for people with dementia: a human rights approach -- tConclusions: grounds for hope -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe time has come to further challenge biomedical and clinical thinking about dementia, which has for so long underpinned policy and practice. Framing dementia as a disability, this book takes a rights-based approach to expand the debate. Applying a social constructionist lens, it builds on earlier critical perspectives by bringing together concepts including disability, social inclusion, personhood, equality, participation, dignity, empowerment, autonomy and solidarity. Launching the debate into new and exciting territory, the book argues that people living with dementia come within the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities and therefore have full entitlement to all the rights the Convention enshrines. A human rights-based approach has not to date been fully applied to interrogate the lived experience and policy response to dementia. With the fresh analytical tools provided in this book, policy makers and practitioners will will gain new insights into how this broader perspective can be used to further promote the quality of life and quality of care for all those affected by dementia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDementiaxPatientsxCare. 0aDementiaxPatientsxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aHuman rights. 0aMental health laws. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aFlynn, Eilionóir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831111966640 cprintz978144733140740uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447331384?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447331384423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447331384/original  a978-3-11-119666-4  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles